ork in the context of the United States. The book not only highlights the differences between these organizations and traditional businesses, but also provides applied chapters on organizational development, strategic management and leadership, human resources, finance, and social accounting and accountability in social economy organizations.The perfect introduction to the social economy framework for students of nonprofit management, business, social entrepreneurship, and public policy, Understanding the Social Economy of the United States an invaluable resource for the classroom and for practitioners working in the social economy sector.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness enterprisesxCase studiesxUnited States. 0aBusiness enterpriseszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aCommunity developmentxUnited States. 0aCommunity developmentzUnited States. 0aCooperative societiesxUnited States. 0aCooperative societieszUnited States. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspectsxUnited States. 0aEconomicszUnited StatesxSociological aspects. 0aNonprofit organizationsxUnited States. 0aNonprofit organizationszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aQuarter, Jack, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWhitman, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266394740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442663947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442663947.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ES